In [6]:
class_names = train_ds.class_names

Prefetching overlaps the preprocessing and model execution of a training step. While the model is executing training step s, the input pipeline is reading the data for step s+1. Doing so reduces the step time to the maximum (as opposed to the sum) of the training and the time it takes to extract the data.

In [7]:
AUTOTUNE = tf.data.experimental.AUTOTUNE

train_ds = train_ds.cache().shuffle(1000).prefetch(buffer_size=AUTOTUNE)
val_ds = val_ds.cache().prefetch(buffer_size=AUTOTUNE)

As a classification algorithm, I decided to use a pre-trained resnet50 on imagenet.

The choice of model was mainly based on two factors:

1) Simplicity of implementation but at the same time ability to recognize images;

2) To develop the "bonus" project, doing some research on the Internet, I found a paper [1] where they used in the first steps the resnet50 model.

[1] https://www.mdpi.com/2313-433X/8/8/215

I also did some data augmentation in order to increment the training set, in particular data augmentation increases the train set simply by taking images and applying random transformations of rotation or scaling.

In [8]:
data_augmentation = tf.keras.Sequential([
    tf.keras.layers.experimental.preprocessing.RandomFlip('horizontal'),
    tf.keras.layers.experimental.preprocessing.RandomRotation(0.2)
])

preprocess_input = tf.keras.applications.resnet.preprocess_input

#The input shape is adapted on the images used to train the model
base_model = tf.keras.applications.resnet.ResNet50(
    input_shape=(100, 100, 3),
    include_top=False,
    weights='imagenet')

#To speed up the training, I froze the weights of the resnet50 network
base_model.trainable = False

global_average_layer = tf.keras.layers.GlobalAveragePooling2D()

#In the output dense layer I entered the number of labels 
prediction_layer = tf.keras.layers.Dense(131)
In [9]:
inputs = tf.keras.Input(shape=(100, 100, 3))
x = data_augmentation(inputs)
x = preprocess_input(x)
x = base_model(x, training=False)
x = global_average_layer(x)
x = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2)(x)
outputs = prediction_layer(x)

model = tf.keras.Model(inputs=inputs, outputs=outputs)
In [10]:
optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.0001)

model.compile(
    optimizer=optimizer,
    loss=tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(from_logits=True),
    metrics=['accuracy']
)

As we can observe above, the model returns very high train and val accuracy values already at the first epoch. As epochs increase train accuracy and validation accuracy increase and simultaneously train loss and val loss decrease consequently the model does not overfit the data.

In [14]:
def predict(model, img):
    img_array = img_to_array(images[i].numpy())
    img_array = tf.expand_dims(img_array, 0)

    predictions = model.predict(img_array)

    predicted_class = class_names[np.argmax(predictions[0])]
    confidence = round(100*(np.max(predictions[0])), 0)
    class_int = np.argmax(predictions[0])
    return predicted_class, confidence, class_int/131

plt.figure(figsize=(25, 40))
for images, labels in test_ds.take(1):
    for i in range(12):
        ax = plt.subplot(4, 3, i+1)
        plt.imshow(images[i].numpy().astype("uint8"))

        predicted_class, confidence, class_int = predict(model, images[i].numpy())
        if confidence < 0:
            confidence = confidence*-1
        actual_class = class_names[labels[i]]

        plt.title(f"Actual: {actual_class}, \n Predicted: {predicted_class}.\n Confidence: {confidence}%")
